*You can use the below implementation of **`addAndMultiply`** method to get the desired result as follows:*

**Logic:**

1) I have first initialised the `result` with the first element of the list and then save the `loopSize` as `size` of the `list`.
2) After that , I have checked whether the `loopSize` is **even or odd**, if even then modified the result by adding the last element of the list and reducing the `loopSize` by 1.
3) Now iterating the list from `i=1` to the `loopSize` with an increment of `i+2` and adding the `result` after multiplying the consecutive numbers as `(list.get(i) * list.get(i + 1))`.


**Code:**

    static int addAndMultiply(List&lt;Integer&gt; list) {
        int result = list.get(0);
        int loopSize = list.size();
        if ((loopSize &amp; 1) !=1) {
            result = result + list.get(loopSize - 1);
            loopSize = loopSize - 1;
        }
        for (int i = 1; i &lt; loopSize; i = i + 2) {
            result = result + (list.get(i) * list.get(i + 1));
        }
        return result;
    }

